{"id":"1210.6251","submitter":"Young S Kim","authors":"Young S. Kim and Marilyn E. Noz","title":"Dirac Matrices and Feynman's Rest of the Universe","comments":"Latex 19 pages with 2 figures. Abstract modified. Minor corrections","journal-ref":"Symmetry 4, 626-643 (2012)","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph hep-th math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  There are two sets of four-by-four matrices introduced by Dirac. The first\nset consists of fifteen Majorana matrices derivable from his four $\\gamma$\nmatrices. These fifteen matrices can also serve as the generators of the group\n$SL(4,r)$. The second set consists of ten generators of the $Sp(4)$ group which\nDirac derived from two coupled harmonic oscillators. It is shown possible to\nextend the symmetry of $Sp(4)$ to that of $SL(4,r)$ if the area of the phase\nspace of one of the oscillators is allowed to become smaller without a lower\nlimit. While there are no restrictions on the size of phase space in classical\nmechanics, Feynman's rest of the universe makes this $Sp(4)$-to-$SL(4,r)$\ntransition possible. The ten generators are for the world where quantum\nmechanics is valid. The remaining five generators belong to the rest of the\nuniverse. It is noted that the groups $SL(4,r)$ and $Sp(4)$ are locally\nisomorphic to the Lorentz groups O(3,3) and O(3,2) respectively. This allows us\nto interpret Feynman's rest of the universe in terms of space-time symmetry.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 23 Oct 2012 14:38:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 1 Nov 2012 14:41:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 3 Jul 2013 13:15:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-07-04"}
