{"id":"1210.6271","submitter":"Alberto Enciso","authors":"Alberto Enciso and Daniel Peralta-Salas","title":"Existence of knotted vortex tubes in steady Euler flows","comments":"61 pages, minor typos corrected","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP math-ph math.DS math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We prove the existence of knotted and linked thin vortex tubes for steady\nsolutions to the incompressible Euler equation in R^3. More precisely, given a\nfinite collection of (possibly linked and knotted) disjoint thin tubes in R^3,\nwe show that they can be transformed with a C^m-small diffeomorphism into a set\nof vortex tubes of a Beltrami field that tends to zero at infinity. The\nstructure of the vortex lines in the tubes is extremely rich, presenting a\npositive-measure set of invariant tori and infinitely many periodic vortex\nlines. The problem of the existence of steady knotted vortex tubes can be\ntraced back to Lord Kelvin.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 23 Oct 2012 15:37:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 23 Oct 2014 10:00:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-10-24"}
